Tue Apr 24 17:57:41 EST 2007



[[[break]]]added at line 28: *lime {code In Defence of Genes as Language

I agree with Stuart.  Especially for his second conclusion (about chemistry being a language).  Here is my argument in support of Genes as Language.

What do we mean by language?  Obviously this is a whole philosophical topic by itself.  But here is my best attempt to pick out the essential features of a language, being as general as possible.  Language is:

-	a means of communication information
-	reasonably constant in meaning:  input x should be understood to give output y regardless of who the input originated from.  
-	able to be broken down into smaller units (such as words) that can be recombined in ways to give new meanings

The genetic code is a composed of the nucleotide bases A, T, G, and C, and these are organised into three letter codon eg. ATG, CAC etc.  Many codons are strung together to form genes (yes, yes, I know – the definition of a gene is controversial.  I have left this definition vague so as to capture both the evolutionary gene of Dawkins, and the standard molecular biology definition:  A gene is the portions of DNA required to give a functional gene product).

Each codon can be ‘read’ by a ribosome, which then attaches a particular amino-acid (the building blocks of proteins) to a growing protein.  The correspondence of each codon to a particular amino-acid forms the basis of the genetic code.

The genetic code has two main features:  It is conserved, and has a high level of redundancy.  By conserved, I mean that correlation of each codon for a certain type of amino-acid is the same (conserved) between almost (but not quite) all types of life:  ATG codes for the amino acid methionine whether you are a human, a plant or a bacterium.  By redundancy, I mean that more than one three-letter combination of A, T, G and C may code for the same amino-acid.  Think of it like synonyms in English – both Cat and Feline can refer to the same thing, just as the codons TCT and AGC both code for the amino acid serine.

So this means the DNA is a way of communicating information (about the sequence different types of amino-acids should come in), it is reasonably constant (because it is conserved) and it can be broken down into smaller units (codons) that can be recombined in many different meaningful (biologically active) ways.

Jason had several points as to why genes don’t count as language.  I will go through them here (and hope Jason will correct any, if I have misunderstood his point):

- genes vary a lot, compared to other things like the cell membranes 

Do they?  Over 90% of the human genome is identical to that of chimpanzees.  So there is an awful lot of similarity between two different species, let alone two members of the same species.  And anyway, flexibility in the way things can be strung together is feature of language.  As for the lecture example of cell membranes being invariant – there are over for different types of phospholipids (the fat molecules that make up cell membranes).  Depending on the type of cell, these are present in different proportions.  Then there are secondary lipid structures, like lipid rafts and invaginations that add yet more complexity.  So cell membranes are by no means simple. 


- genes are just chemistry, and hence not a language

Firstly, this rules out lots of other things (such as computer code) that we might call language, aside from the classical human stuff, because computer code is just minute magnetisations on the surface of a computer hard-disk.

If this view is taken to extremes, then everything is just chemistry.  Human language is just extra complicated chemistry carried out by rather large bags of chemicals called humans, mediated by chemicals called neurotransmitters within our brains.  So it seems perfectly ok for language to be composed to chemistry.

There is the question of whether language requires a conscious agent to produce it.  The use of the word language for animal-animal and robot-robot communication suggests that at some level at least, it doesn’t.

- Genes-As-Language leads us to Genes-As-Instructions, and this downplays the importance of the rest of the machinery

I agree with this statement – and don’t think that this is a bad thing, so long as the importance of the rest of the machinery isn’t reduced to nothing!  Genes ARE very important for all living things.  The number of diseases caused by genetic defects is huge, and the number of diseases that people can become resistant to through possessing certain genotypes is also huge (resistance to malaria from sickle cell and resistance to tuberculosis from heterozygote cystic fibrosis are two examples).  No organism can develop without genes.

To conclude, I would describes genes as language, and as instructions, although not complete ones:  

Genes are necessary but not sufficient for life.

Perhaps the best analogy I have ever heard (from a 1st year bio course) was to regard genes as cooking recipes.  Recipes are not exhaustive – they tell you want ingredients to use, but assume that you will know what temperature a moderate oven is, that you have to break open the eggs before mixing them into the batter, to mix things in a bowl not an egg cup etc.  Genes will tell you want amino-acids to use, but the rest follows automatically from the environmental homeostasis (control of environment) that all life forms have.

Cheers,
Morgan Sheridan

----

}*
