[[[break]]]added at line 0: *lime {code Today we wrapped up our discussion of genes as instructions. I think the angle he attacked the computer program analogy from was a little misleading.

Jason's argument seemed came from the perspective of the programmer, someone writing code in a human readable computer language. This is analagous, I think, to a god writing an organism's genome in a god readable language, and having it compiled into DNA. The conclusion he draws from this analogy is most certainly correct, but I think it's the wrong perspective.

I think the analogy works best when we look at a program from the machine's perspective. When a program is compiled, it is translated into a stream of bits (1s and 0s). When a program is executed, the bits are interpreted by the CPU into the appropriate instruction, which might be an add, a multiplication, a bit-shift operation etc. 

I think this is very much like what seems to be happening in genetics. Replace the bits with the bases and we get an analogy that works quite well. How the bases are ordered and paired has an influence over the effect of that DNA. Similarly, the ordering of the bits in a program influences what the effects of the program are.

When interpreted by the computer a stream of bits has a meaning, it is in essence a language. When a human looks at the bit stream, it's literally just a bunch of 1s and 0s (although we can force ourselves to think like a machine however, as we did design the way they work). This is where the difference that Jason is worried about could be seen to appear. To us, the base sequence of DNA could look like a language, that we could interpret as instructions, but to the DNA, it's just chemistry, as Jason says.

I'm still not sure if I completely agree with this conclusion, as I believe that the mere fact that we give a language to chemistry:
(
  H          O - H
    \        /
H - C - C - H 
     /       \
    H        H               anyone?)

that we might as well act as if it is coded. But this has more to do with my philosophy of science than simply genetics by itself.

Feel free to tear this apart as much as you like, Jason.

Stuart

